        body: "Diabetic foot infections (DFIs) are a leading cause of hospitalisation and amputation, with up to 60% of DFUs becoming infected over their clinical course. Increased susceptibility reflects multiple converging immune deficits characteristic of diabetes.\n\n**Why Diabetic Patients Are More Susceptible**\n\nHyperglycaemia impairs neutrophil chemotaxis, phagocytosis, and intracellular killing — all three core components of innate immune defence against bacterial invasion. Glycation of immunoglobulins reduces their opsonising efficiency. Concurrent microvascular disease impairs delivery of immune cells and antibiotics to the infected tissue, while neuropathy delays presentation since pain — normally an early warning sign of infection — may be absent or blunted.\n\n**Recognising Infection in the Neuropathic Foot**\n\nClassical signs of infection (warmth, erythema, swelling, pain) may all be attenuated or absent. Clinicians must maintain a high index of suspicion for any wound with malodour, friable or discoloured granulation tissue, increased exudate, delayed healing despite appropriate offloading, or new-onset hyperglycaemia in a previously controlled patient — this last sign can be the only clue to an occult infection.\n\n**Osteomyelitis: A Diagnostic Challenge**\n\nOsteomyelitis complicates up to 20% of DFIs and dramatically worsens prognosis if missed. The probe-to-bone test (detailed later in this course) remains the most accessible bedside screening tool. MRI is the gold-standard imaging modality, with sensitivity around 90% and specificity around 80%, substantially outperforming plain radiography, which may show no changes for 10-14 days after bone infection begins.\n\n**MRSA and Resistant Organisms**\n\nMRSA colonisation rates in chronic DFUs range from 10-30% in UK cohorts, and prior antibiotic exposure, prior hospitalisation, and chronic wound duration all increase risk. Empirical antibiotic choice should always be guided by local antimicrobial resistance patterns and microbiology results once available, rather than fixed protocols applied uniformly.\n\n**Differentiating Soft Tissue Infection from Osteomyelitis Clinically**\n\nBeyond the probe-to-bone test, several additional clinical and laboratory clues help distinguish osteomyelitis from soft tissue infection alone. A wound area exceeding 2cm squared, wound duration beyond several weeks, and visible or palpable bone are all individually associated with increased osteomyelitis likelihood. Inflammatory markers, particularly ESR above 70mm/hr, lend additional support to a diagnosis of osteomyelitis, though normal inflammatory markers do not reliably exclude it, particularly in early or localised bone infection. No single clinical or laboratory finding is sufficiently sensitive or specific in isolation — osteomyelitis diagnosis typically requires synthesis of clinical findings, probe-to-bone result, and imaging, reflecting the genuinely challenging nature of this diagnosis even for experienced clinicians.",
