        id: "d6", heading: "IWGDF 2023 Risk Classification",
        body: "The International Working Group on the Diabetic Foot (IWGDF) risk classification system provides the internationally recognised framework for stratifying ulceration risk and determining review frequency. Applying it consistently and accurately is a core competency expected of every podiatrist working with patients with diabetes.\n\n**Risk Category 0: Low Risk**\n\nNo loss of protective sensation (LOPS), no peripheral arterial disease (PAD). Annual structured foot assessment is sufficient, alongside basic foot care education covering daily inspection, appropriate footwear, and nail care.\n\n**Risk Category 1: Moderate Risk**\n\nLOPS present, or PAD present, but not both, and no significant deformity. Six-monthly specialist podiatry review. At this stage, education must specifically address that pain can no longer be relied upon as a warning sign — visual self-inspection becomes the primary protective behaviour.\n\n**Risk Category 2: High Risk**\n\nLOPS plus PAD, or LOPS plus significant foot deformity, or PAD plus significant foot deformity. Three-monthly review, with vascular assessment incorporated at each visit. Custom footwear or orthoses should be actively considered where deformity contributes to abnormal pressure distribution.\n\n**Risk Category 3: Very High Risk**\n\nHistory of foot ulceration, history of lower-limb amputation (partial or complete, at any level), or end-stage renal disease (added to the classification in the 2023 update, reflecting emerging evidence of its independent contribution to ulceration risk). Review every one to three months, coordinated through the specialist diabetic foot multidisciplinary team. NICE NG19 mandates MDT referral within 24 hours of any active diabetic foot problem in this group — a service standard, not a guideline suggestion, reflecting the urgency genuinely warranted.\n\n**Why Consistent Application Matters**\n\nMisclassification in either direction has real consequences: under-classification delays necessary intensification of care, while over-classification places unnecessary burden on limited specialist capacity. Accurate, consistent risk stratification at every assessment is therefore not an administrative exercise but a direct clinical safety mechanism.",
