          q: "The core principle of moisture management in wound healing is best described as:",
          options: ["Maximising moisture at all times", "Achieving moisture balance matched to the wound's actual current exudate level", "Keeping all wounds completely dry", "Moisture level has no clinical relevance"],
          answer: 1,
          explain: "The goal is moisture balance, not moisture maximisation — neither too dry (impairing cellular migration) nor too wet (causing maceration). Dressing selection should be matched to and actively reassessed against the wound's actual current exudate level at every visit."
