      {
        id: "w20", heading: "Wound Care Evidence and Clinical Governance",
        body: "This concluding slide draws together the evidence-based principles established throughout this course into a coherent framework for ongoing evidence-based practice and clinical governance in wound care.\n\n**The Evidence Hierarchy Applied to Wound Care**\n\nAs emphasised throughout this course — from Winter's foundational moist wound healing research through the Cochrane review evidence on specific interventions covered in the Wound Dressings and Topical Therapies course — wound care practice should be grounded in the best available evidence, applying a consistent hierarchy: systematic reviews and meta-analyses, individual randomised controlled trials, then observational and cohort studies, with manufacturer-funded case series carrying appropriately less evidential weight despite frequently prominent marketing.\n\n**Avoiding Common Evidence-Practice Gaps**\n\nThis course has highlighted several areas where genuine evidence-practice gaps persist in routine clinical settings — total contact cast underuse despite strong evidence (covered in the Diabetic Foot course), inconsistent application of the validated four-week reassessment milestone, and continued use of wound swabs in clinically uninfected wounds despite limited evidence value. Recognising and actively addressing these evidence-practice gaps in one's own clinical practice is a genuine professional responsibility, not merely an academic exercise.\n\n**Clinical Governance Principles**\n\nRobust clinical governance in wound care services encompasses: consistent application of evidence-based protocols and pathways, systematic audit and outcome measurement as covered in the dedicated earlier slide, appropriate incident reporting and learning when complications or adverse outcomes occur, and ongoing practitioner education ensuring practice keeps pace with evolving evidence rather than relying indefinitely on training received early in a clinical career.\n\n**The Practitioner's Ongoing Responsibility**\n\nWound care evidence continues to evolve, and maintaining genuinely current practice requires ongoing engagement with new evidence as it emerges, critical appraisal skills to evaluate new claims (applying the evidence hierarchy and evaluation framework covered throughout this curriculum) rather than uncritical adoption of new products or techniques based on marketing claims alone, and willingness to actively change established practice when genuinely robust new evidence warrants it.\n\n**Closing Synthesis**\n\nThe wound assessment and management principles developed across this course — accurate aetiology determination, the TIME framework for wound bed preparation, evidence-based dressing selection, compression and offloading where indicated, accurate infection recognition, and the special population and governance considerations covered in these final slides — together form a comprehensive, evidence-based foundation for competent, safe, and effective wound care practice, to be continually refined and updated as both individual clinical experience and the broader evidence base continue to develop throughout a podiatric career.",
        quiz: {
          q: "When evaluating evidence for a new wound care product or technique, the evidence hierarchy places greatest weight on:",
          options: ["Manufacturer-funded case series", "Systematic reviews and meta-analyses, followed by individual RCTs", "Marketing materials and testimonials", "Personal anecdotal experience alone"],
          answer: 1,
          explain: "The evidence hierarchy places greatest weight on systematic reviews and meta-analyses, followed by individual randomised controlled trials, then observational studies — with manufacturer-funded case series carrying appropriately less evidential weight despite often prominent marketing."
        }
      }
