        id: "b15", heading: "Plantar Fasciopathy: Evidence-Based Management",
        body: "Plantar fasciopathy management should follow an evidence-based hierarchy, building directly on the risk factor and diagnostic understanding established in the previous slide.\n\n**First-Line Conservative Management**\n\nCalf and plantar fascia-specific stretching, addressing the ankle equinus risk factor established earlier in this course, forms appropriate first-line management alongside activity modification and, where elevated BMI is a contributing factor, weight management discussion.\n\n**Foot Orthoses**\n\nAs established in the orthotic theory slide, both custom and well-fitted prefabricated orthoses demonstrate comparable evidence for plantar fasciopathy management, supporting orthotic intervention as an appropriate component of management without necessarily requiring costly custom devices as a default first approach.\n\n**Intrinsic Muscle Strengthening**\n\nGiven the established contribution of intrinsic foot muscle weakness to plantar fasciopathy risk (as covered in the Foot and Ankle Anatomy course), specific intrinsic strengthening exercises, including the short foot exercise, represent an increasingly evidence-supported component of comprehensive management programmes.\n\n**Extracorporeal Shockwave Therapy**\n\nFor chronic plantar fasciopathy refractory to standard conservative management beyond approximately 3 months, extracorporeal shockwave therapy (ESWT) demonstrates the strongest evidence base among escalation options, with Rompe et al. (2010, AJSM) reporting 60-80% good to excellent outcomes in appropriately selected chronic presentations.\n\n**A Structured, Stepped Management Approach**\n\nEffective plantar fasciopathy management follows a structured, stepped approach — addressing modifiable risk factors and providing first-line conservative management initially, escalating to orthotic intervention and structured strengthening where first-line measures prove insufficient, and reserving ESWT or further escalation for genuinely chronic, treatment-refractory presentations — reflecting the evidence-based, individualised clinical reasoning approach developed consistently throughout this course rather than applying every available intervention simultaneously regardless of presentation chronicity or severity.",
