        id: "b17", heading: "Medial Tibial Stress Syndrome and Stress Fractures",
        body: "Medial tibial stress syndrome (MTSS, commonly termed \"shin splints\") and tibial stress fractures represent related but distinct presentations along a bone stress injury spectrum, with accurate differentiation directly informing management.\n\n**MTSS: Presentation and Mechanism**\n\nMTSS presents as diffuse pain along the distal two-thirds of the posteromedial tibial border, tender over a broad area — this diffuse tenderness pattern is a key distinguishing feature from the more focal point tenderness characteristic of stress fracture, covered below. MTSS represents a periosteal traction injury at the origin of soleus and flexor digitorum longus, exacerbated by repetitive tibial bending forces during running and other repetitive loading activities.\n\n**MTSS Risk Factors**\n\nExcessive subtalar joint pronation, increased navicular drop (as covered in the Foot and Ankle Anatomy course), reduced ankle dorsiflexion range, female sex, and previous MTSS history (a notably strong predictor of recurrence) are all established risk factors, alongside rapid training volume increases and running on hard or cambered surfaces as common precipitating factors.\n\n**Tibial Stress Fractures: A Distinguishing Pattern**\n\nUnlike MTSS's diffuse tenderness pattern, tibial stress fractures typically present with focal, point tenderness at a discrete location along the tibia, often with associated localised swelling — this focal-versus-diffuse tenderness distinction is the most clinically useful bedside discriminator between the two presentations, though imaging may still be required where genuine diagnostic uncertainty persists.\n\n**Imaging Considerations**\n\nPlain radiographs are frequently normal in early stress fractures, with sensitivity as low as 15-35% in the first 2-3 weeks following symptom onset. MRI represents the gold-standard imaging modality for early diagnosis when plain radiographs are normal but clinical suspicion remains, additionally providing grading of stress reaction severity that assists in management planning.\n\n**Management Principles**\n\nMTSS management combines relative rest (load reduction rather than complete activity cessation) with addressing biomechanical contributors: foot orthoses reducing excessive pronation have systematic review evidence supporting benefit, and the gait retraining cadence modification covered in the previous slide similarly reduces tibial bending moments. Confirmed tibial stress fractures require load modification, cross-training to maintain fitness during the required rest period, and a graduated, criteria-based return-to-running protocol, covered in detail in the Sports Podiatry course.",
