        id: "b18", heading: "Adult-Acquired Flatfoot Deformity",
        body: "Adult-acquired flatfoot deformity (AAFD), most commonly resulting from tibialis posterior tendon dysfunction (PTTD), represents a progressive condition requiring accurate staging to guide appropriate conservative or surgical management.\n\n**Pathophysiology**\n\nAs established in the Foot and Ankle Anatomy course, tibialis posterior is the primary dynamic stabiliser of the medial longitudinal arch. Progressive tendon dysfunction — from tenosynovitis through partial tearing to complete rupture — produces the staged spectrum of AAFD, frequently occurring alongside spring ligament insufficiency given the close anatomical relationship between these two structures established in the Foot and Ankle Anatomy course.\n\n**The Johnson and Strom Staging System**\n\nStage I: tenosynovitis with normal tendon length and no visible deformity, single-leg heel rise preserved. Stage II: tendon elongation or partial rupture with flexible flatfoot deformity — the \"too many toes\" sign becomes positive (as covered in the observational gait analysis slide earlier in this course), and single-leg heel rise is impaired or absent with failure of heel inversion. Stage III: progression to rigid, fixed flatfoot deformity with secondary subtalar joint arthritic change. Stage IV (added by Myerson): additional ankle valgus deformity from deltoid ligament insufficiency.\n\n**Clinical Assessment Integration**\n\nDiagnosis integrates the single-leg heel rise test and \"too many toes\" sign covered in earlier slides of this course, alongside palpation of the tibialis posterior tendon course for tenderness or swelling, and assessment of whether the flatfoot deformity is flexible (Stage I-II) or rigid (Stage III-IV) — this flexibility assessment directly determines whether conservative orthotic management remains viable or surgical intervention becomes the primary consideration.\n\n**Management by Stage**\n\nStage I-II generally responds to custom functional orthoses providing significant medial arch support, combined with tibialis posterior strengthening exercises. Stage III-IV, given the rigid deformity and arthritic change, generally requires surgical intervention (ranging from tendon transfer and osteotomy procedures in Stage III to more extensive reconstruction or fusion procedures in Stage IV), reflecting that conservative management's effectiveness diminishes substantially once rigid deformity has developed.",
