        id: "b19", heading: "Biomechanics of Common Running Injuries",
        body: "Running injuries represent among the most frequent presentations in active podiatric patients, and understanding their underlying biomechanical risk factors enables meaningful, evidence-based clinical contribution to their management.\n\n**Iliotibial Band Syndrome (ITBS)**\n\nITBS presents as lateral knee pain developing at a consistent distance into a run, as the IT band compresses between the lateral femoral epicondyle and Gerdy's tubercle at approximately 30 degrees of knee flexion — the specific impingement angle corresponding to the loading response phase of gait. Biomechanical risk factors include hip abductor weakness (driving increased hip adduction and internal rotation) and increased contralateral pelvic drop during single-limb stance.\n\n**ITBS Management**\n\nGait retraining to increase step rate by 5-10% reduces knee flexion angle at foot strike and has strong evidence support alongside hip abductor strengthening as the primary evidence-based ITBS management approaches, reflecting the same cadence modification principle applied to MTSS and PFPS covered in earlier slides.\n\n**Medial Tibial Stress Syndrome Recap**\n\nAs established in the previous slide, MTSS responds to STJ pronation control via foot orthoses and the same cadence-increasing gait retraining approach applied across multiple running-related overuse conditions covered in this course.\n\n**The Recurring Cadence Modification Theme**\n\nA notable pattern emerging across this course's coverage of running-related injuries — PFPS, ITBS, and MTSS — is the consistent evidence supporting cadence modification (increasing step rate by 5-10%) as a relatively simple, low-cost intervention with genuine RCT support across multiple distinct injury presentations, reflecting that this single biomechanical modification (reducing stride length, vertical displacement, and ground reaction force impulse) addresses a shared underlying loading mechanism contributing to several different specific injury presentations.\n\n**Integrating Running Injury Biomechanics with Broader Course Principles**\n\nThe biomechanical reasoning applied throughout this slide and the preceding running-related injury content draws directly on the foundational gait cycle, ground reaction force, and kinetic chain principles established earlier in this course — demonstrating how the structured biomechanical assessment and reasoning framework developed throughout this curriculum applies consistently across the diverse range of specific clinical presentations a podiatrist will encounter in active patient populations.",
