        id: "b20", heading: "Clinical Biomechanics: Synthesis and Evidence-Based Practice",
        body: "This concluding slide draws together the biomechanical assessment, gait analysis, and condition-specific management principles developed throughout this course into an integrated framework for evidence-based clinical biomechanical practice.\n\n**The Structured Assessment Framework**\n\nThis course has established a consistent assessment sequence: non-weight-bearing structural assessment (joint range of motion, muscle length), static weight-bearing assessment, functional testing under load (single-leg heel rise, windlass test), and gait observation from multiple viewing angles — together building a comprehensive clinical picture rather than relying on any single assessment component in isolation.\n\n**The Tissue Stress Model as a Unifying Principle**\n\nThe shift from structural correction toward tissue stress-based clinical reasoning, established early in this course, has recurred throughout subsequent condition-specific content — orthotic prescription, tendinopathy management, and running injury biomechanics all reflect this same underlying principle: identifying and reducing load on the specific symptomatic tissue, rather than pursuing a generic structural \"correction\" disconnected from the patient's actual presenting symptoms.\n\n**Evidence-Based Loading as a Recurring Theme**\n\nAcross tendinopathy, plantar fasciopathy, and running injury management, this course has consistently emphasised evidence-based progressive loading principles (eccentric and heavy slow resistance protocols, intrinsic strengthening, cadence modification) over passive treatment approaches, reflecting the broader shift in musculoskeletal rehabilitation toward active, loading-based management strategies supported by robust contemporary evidence.\n\n**Integrating Biomechanics with the Wider Podiatric Curriculum**\n\nThe biomechanical assessment and reasoning skills developed throughout this course directly underpin clinical practice across the wider podiatric curriculum — informing diabetic foot offloading decisions (Diabetic Foot course), surgical planning considerations (Nail Pathology course), wound-related mechanical factors (Wound Assessment course), and sport-specific injury management (Sports Podiatry course) — reflecting biomechanics not as an isolated subspecialty but as a foundational clinical reasoning framework applicable across virtually all areas of podiatric practice.\n\n**Continuing Professional Development in Biomechanics**\n\nGiven the continuing evolution of biomechanical evidence — from the historical structural correction model toward the contemporary tissue stress model covered throughout this course — maintaining genuinely current practice requires ongoing engagement with emerging evidence and willingness to update established clinical approaches as the evidence base continues to develop, a responsibility extending well beyond the completion of this course alone.",
