        id: "p4", heading: "Flexible Flatfoot and the Jack Test",
        body: "Flexible flatfoot is among the most common parental concerns presenting to paediatric podiatric practice, and the Jack test provides the defining clinical assessment distinguishing this benign presentation from genuine structural pathology.\n\n**The Jack (Windlass) Test**\n\nAs established in the Foot and Ankle Anatomy course, the Jack test assesses whether the arch reconstitutes when the child stands on tiptoe or when the hallux is passively dorsiflexed — confirming the deformity is genuinely flexible rather than structurally rigid, by activating the windlass mechanism to demonstrate the arch is mechanically intact despite its flattened resting appearance.\n\n**Management of Asymptomatic Flexible Flatfoot**\n\nAn asymptomatic child with flexible flatfoot, normal activity levels, and no reported pain requires no intervention beyond reassurance regarding the normal developmental nature of this presentation, established in the earlier normal foot development slide. There is no good evidence that orthoses prevent progression to symptomatic flatfoot in asymptomatic children, though orthotic intervention may provide symptomatic relief if genuine pain or activity-limiting fatigue is present.\n\n**Tarsal Coalition: The Important Rigid Differential**\n\nTarsal coalition presents very differently from flexible flatfoot: a painful, rigid flatfoot, typically presenting at ages 8-16 years — corresponding to the period of coalition ossification — distinguishing it clearly from the earlier-presenting, asymptomatic flexible flatfoot covered above.\n\n**Imaging for Suspected Tarsal Coalition**\n\nCalcaneonavicular coalition is best visualised on oblique foot radiograph; talocalcaneal coalition requires CT or MRI for diagnosis given its less straightforward radiographic visualisation. Any rigid, painful flatfoot presenting in this age range warrants imaging investigation rather than the reassurance-based approach appropriate for flexible flatfoot.\n\n**The Critical Clinical Distinction**\n\nThe Jack test, combined with the age and pain pattern considerations above, provides the essential clinical framework for distinguishing the overwhelmingly common, benign flexible flatfoot from the much rarer but clinically significant tarsal coalition — a distinction with substantially different management and investigation implications, making accurate application of this assessment framework a core paediatric podiatric clinical skill.",
