        id: "p5", heading: "Severs Disease (Calcaneal Apophysitis)",
        body: "Severs disease is the most common cause of heel pain in children aged 8-15 years, and understanding its mechanism as a traction apophysitis directly explains both its presentation and its universally excellent prognosis.\n\n**The Calcaneal Apophysis**\n\nAs established in the Foot and Ankle Anatomy course, the calcaneal apophysis ossifies at approximately age 7-8 and fuses with the calcaneal body at 12-15 years — Severs disease occurs specifically during this vulnerable window while the apophysis remains unfused.\n\n**Mechanism: Traction During Growth Spurts**\n\nDuring periods of rapid growth, the calcaneus lengthens faster than the Achilles tendon and plantar fascia attached to it, applying traction forces to the relatively weak, unfused apophysis — this growth-rate mismatch, rather than any structural abnormality, is the fundamental mechanism underlying this condition.\n\n**Clinical Presentation**\n\nBilateral presentation occurs in approximately 60% of cases. Pain is typically activity-related, characteristically worse with running and jumping sports, and relieved by rest — direct posterior heel tenderness on compression (the \"squeeze test\") supports the clinical diagnosis without requiring routine imaging in typical presentations.\n\n**Management: Activity Modification, Not Cessation**\n\nManagement centres on relative activity modification (reducing but not necessarily completely stopping sporting activity), heel raises (6-10mm) placed in both shoes to reduce Achilles tendon traction force, calf stretching, padded heel cups for symptomatic relief, and ice application following activity.\n\n**A Universally Excellent Prognosis**\n\nCritically, and in clear contrast to many of the conditions covered elsewhere in this course, Severs disease prognosis is universally excellent — resolution is guaranteed once the calcaneal apophysis fuses with the calcaneal body, providing genuine, confident reassurance that should be clearly communicated to anxious parents and young patients alike, distinguishing this self-limiting growth-related condition from pathology requiring more uncertain long-term management.",
