        body: "Juvenile idiopathic arthritis (JIA) commonly affects the foot and ankle, and podiatric assessment can play a genuinely important early diagnostic role given the frequent early involvement of these joints.\n\n**Early Foot and Ankle Involvement**\n\nThe subtalar and midtarsal joints are frequently involved early in JIA's disease course — sometimes before knee or hand involvement becomes clinically apparent — making podiatric assessment potentially significant in early diagnosis, particularly where a child presents with foot-related symptoms not yet recognised as part of a broader systemic process.\n\n**Clinical Features**\n\nMorning stiffness lasting more than 30 minutes, joint swelling, and a limp are characteristic features — importantly, the limp may be the presenting complaint rather than overt reported pain, since children frequently under-report joint pain compared with adults, making behavioural and functional changes (reluctance to walk, altered gait pattern) potentially more clinically informative than direct pain reporting in younger children specifically.\n\n**Tenosynovitis as a Mimicking Presentation**\n\nTenosynovitis, particularly affecting tibialis posterior, is common in JIA and can mimic mechanical flatfoot presentations if the examiner does not specifically assess for synovial swelling along the tendon sheath — this is an important differential consideration when a child presents with apparent flatfoot deformity, since the underlying mechanism (inflammatory tenosynovitis versus mechanical/structural flatfoot) has substantially different management implications.\n\n**Podiatric Management Within the Broader MDT**\n\nPodiatric management focuses on accommodative orthoses reducing pain and protecting affected joints, appropriate footwear with adequate depth to accommodate joint swelling, and close liaison with the paediatric rheumatology team managing the underlying systemic inflammatory process — podiatric input represents one component of genuinely multidisciplinary JIA management rather than a standalone treatment approach.\n\n**When to Consider Rheumatological Referral**\n\nAny child presenting with unexplained foot pain, swelling, or limp persisting beyond 6 weeks should be considered for rheumatological referral to exclude JIA, reflecting that persistent, otherwise unexplained lower limb symptoms in children warrant consideration of this differential alongside the more commonly considered mechanical and developmental causes covered elsewhere in this course.",
