        id: "p10", heading: "Cerebral Palsy: Foot and Ankle Management",
        body: "Cerebral palsy (CP) produces characteristic foot and ankle deformities resulting from spasticity, muscle imbalance, and abnormal growth patterns, requiring genuinely multidisciplinary management informed by understanding the underlying neurological mechanism.\n\n**Equinus as the Most Common Presentation**\n\nEquinus deformity from gastrocnemius-soleus spasticity is the most common foot and ankle presentation in CP, producing the characteristic toe-walking gait pattern frequently the most visible and earliest-recognised feature of lower limb involvement.\n\n**Pattern Variation by CP Subtype**\n\nEquinovarus deformity (combined equinus and hindfoot varus) is common in hemiplegic and some diplegic presentations, while planovalgus deformity (flatfoot with hindfoot valgus) is more common in diplegic and quadriplegic patterns — these differing deformity patterns reflect different underlying patterns of spasticity distribution and weight-bearing characteristics between CP subtypes.\n\n**Ankle-Foot Orthoses**\n\nAFOs represent a foundational management tool, controlling equinus deformity and providing stability during gait, with specific AFO design (rigid versus hinged, degree of ankle control) individualised based on the specific deformity pattern and functional goals for each child.\n\n**Botulinum Toxin and Serial Casting**\n\nBotulinum toxin injections to gastrocnemius-soleus temporarily reduce spasticity and improve range of motion, providing a valuable window for stretching and orthotic management, while serial casting addresses fixed contracture through progressive, gradual correction over successive cast applications.\n\n**Surgical Intervention**\n\nSurgical intervention (tendon lengthening, tendon transfer procedures) is reserved for fixed deformities unresponsive to conservative management, with gait analysis — covered in principle in the Biomechanics and Orthotics course — particularly valuable for surgical planning in complex presentations, allowing objective, detailed characterisation of gait pattern beyond what observational assessment alone can capture.\n\n**Genuinely Multidisciplinary Management**\n\nCP foot and ankle management exemplifies genuinely multidisciplinary care, requiring close coordination between podiatry, physiotherapy, orthopaedics, and orthotics services, with the podiatrist's specific contribution centred on foot and ankle-specific orthotic provision, footwear guidance, and ongoing monitoring for progressive deformity requiring escalation to more intensive intervention.",
