        id: "p11", heading: "Talipes Equinovarus (Clubfoot)",
        body: "Congenital talipes equinovarus (clubfoot) is among the most significant congenital foot deformities encountered in paediatric podiatric and orthopaedic practice, with the Ponseti method representing one of the genuine treatment success stories in this field.\n\n**Epidemiology and Presentation**\n\nAffecting approximately 1 in 1000 live births, with bilateral involvement in 50% of cases and a notable male predominance (approximately 2:1), clubfoot comprises four components remembered by the mnemonic CAVE: Cavus (midfoot), Adduction (forefoot), Varus (hindfoot), Equinus (hindfoot).\n\n**The Ponseti Method: Sequence and Evidence**\n\nThe Ponseti method achieves excellent outcomes in more than 90% of cases without extensive surgery, beginning with serial manipulation and casting shortly after birth, correcting the deformity components in a specific sequence: cavus first, then adduction and varus together, with equinus corrected last — equinus correction frequently requires a percutaneous Achilles tenotomy as the final step of the correction sequence.\n\n**Post-Correction Bracing Protocol**\n\nFollowing successful correction, a foot abduction brace (Denis Browne bar) must be worn 23 hours daily for approximately 3 months, then reduced to nighttime and nap wear until approximately age 4-5 years — this prolonged bracing protocol is essential to maintaining the correction achieved through casting.\n\n**Relapse and the Critical Importance of Bracing Adherence**\n\nRelapse occurs in up to 30% of cases, and critically, relapse is predominantly related to brace non-compliance rather than treatment failure of the initial Ponseti correction itself — this makes family education about the genuine, critical importance of bracing adherence throughout the prolonged protocol absolutely essential to achieving the long-term success the Ponseti method is capable of delivering.\n\n**The Podiatrist's Role in Ongoing Management**\n\nWhile the initial Ponseti correction is typically delivered by specialist orthopaedic services, podiatrists may be involved in ongoing monitoring, footwear guidance during and following the bracing period, and identifying early signs of relapse — supporting the broader treatment team in maximising long-term functional outcomes for affected children.",
