      { q: "Which feature most suggests juvenile idiopathic arthritis rather than mechanical joint pain in a child?", opts: ["Pain that worsens through activity and eases with rest","Early-morning joint stiffness that eases as the day goes on","Pain only when wearing shoes","Symmetrical flexible flat feet"], a: 1, exp: "Inflammatory joint disease characteristically produces early-morning stiffness and \u2018gelling\u2019 after rest that improves with movement, whereas mechanical pain typically worsens with activity \u2014 a key discriminator prompting paediatric rheumatology referral." },
      { q: "Osgood-Schlatter disease causes activity-related pain and tenderness at the:", opts: ["Calcaneal apophysis (heel)", "Tibial tuberosity, at the patellar tendon insertion", "Navicular", "Base of the fifth metatarsal"], a: 1, exp: "Osgood-Schlatter disease is a traction apophysitis at the tibial tuberosity where the patellar tendon inserts, causing activity-related anterior knee pain in adolescents; like Sever\u2019s disease it is self-limiting and managed with load modification." },
      { q: "The CAVE mnemonic for congenital talipes equinovarus components stands for:", opts: ["Cavus, Adduction, Varus, Equinus", "Calcaneus, Ankle, Valgus, Eversion", "Contracture, Achilles, Varus, Extension", "Cavus, Abduction, Valgus, Equinus"], a: 0, exp: "CAVE describes the four components of clubfoot: Cavus (midfoot), Adduction (forefoot), Varus (hindfoot), Equinus (hindfoot) — corrected in this specific sequence by the Ponseti method, with equinus corrected last via Achilles tenotomy." }
