        id: "s7", heading: "Iliotibial Band Syndrome",
        body: "Iliotibial band syndrome (ITBS) is among the most common overuse running injuries, and the biomechanical mechanism established in the Biomechanics and Orthotics course translates directly into the running-specific clinical presentation and management covered in this slide.\n\n**Clinical Presentation**\n\nITBS presents as lateral knee pain typically developing at a consistent distance into a run (the \"impingement point\") rather than from the outset of activity — this consistent-distance pattern is a distinctive diagnostic feature distinguishing ITBS from other lateral knee pain presentations.\n\n**The Impingement Mechanism Recap**\n\nAs established in the Biomechanics and Orthotics course, the IT band compresses against the lateral femoral epicondyle at approximately 30 degrees of knee flexion — the critical impingement angle corresponding to the loading response phase of gait.\n\n**Why Downhill Running Dramatically Worsens ITBS**\n\nDownhill running dramatically exacerbates ITBS by increasing the proportion of the gait cycle spent at the critical 30-degree impingement angle and increasing eccentric loading demands on the IT band-tensor fasciae latae complex — directly explaining a commonly reported pattern where runners notice symptoms specifically or predominantly during downhill sections.\n\n**Biomechanical Risk Factors**\n\nHip abductor weakness (driving increased hip adduction and internal rotation during stance) and increased contralateral pelvic drop represent the primary established biomechanical risk factors, reflecting the proximal kinetic chain contribution established in the Biomechanics and Orthotics course's patellofemoral pain content.\n\n**Evidence-Based Management**\n\nManagement combines activity modification (temporary reduction or cessation of downhill running specifically, given its disproportionate symptom-provoking effect established above), hip abductor strengthening (gluteus medius specifically, the primary evidence-based intervention), and gait retraining to increase step rate by 5-10% — reducing knee flexion angle at foot strike and consequently reducing time spent at the critical impingement angle, applying the same cadence modification principle established across multiple conditions throughout this course.",
