        body: "Plantar fasciopathy in runners shares its core pathophysiology with the general population presentation established in the Biomechanics and Orthotics course, but differs meaningfully in risk factor emphasis and requires specific differential diagnosis consideration in athletic patients.\n\n**Differing Risk Factor Emphasis**\n\nWhile ankle equinus remains a key risk factor as established in the Biomechanics and Orthotics course, rapid training volume increase is the dominant precipitating factor in athletic populations specifically, rather than elevated BMI — which carries less relevance in trained runners, who typically present with lower BMI than the general population in whom the BMI association was originally established.\n\n**Differential Diagnosis Requiring Particular Care**\n\nCalcaneal stress fracture can mimic plantar fasciopathy but presents with more diffuse heel pain and a positive squeeze test (mediolateral calcaneal compression reproducing pain) — an important differential given the stress fracture imaging and management considerations established earlier in this course. Baxter nerve entrapment (affecting the first branch of the lateral plantar nerve) can similarly mimic plantar fasciopathy but presents with associated lateral foot numbness or burning, reflecting a genuinely different underlying pathology requiring different management.\n\n**Management Following the Standard Evidence Hierarchy**\n\nManagement follows the standard evidence-based hierarchy established in the Biomechanics and Orthotics course — stretching, orthoses, intrinsic strengthening, and ESWT for chronic, refractory cases — with running-specific modification favouring temporary training volume reduction rather than complete cessation where pain genuinely allows continued, modified activity.\n\n**Pain-Monitored Graduated Return to Running**\n\nCareful graduated return to running once symptoms substantially improve is typically guided by a pain-monitoring approach similar to the tendinopathy rehabilitation principles established in the Biomechanics and Orthotics course — acceptable pain up to 3-4/10, not worsening over the subsequent 24 hours, providing the same evidence-based load monitoring framework applied across multiple running-related conditions throughout this course.",
