        id: "s10", heading: "Return to Running After Injury",
        body: "Structured return-to-running protocols reduce re-injury risk compared with ad-hoc, unstructured resumption of training, providing essential clinical guidance following the range of running injuries covered throughout this course.\n\n**The Graduated Framework**\n\nA graduated framework typically progresses through walk-run intervals, continuous easy running, then progressive volume and intensity increases, with clear criteria for progression at each stage — rather than the time-based progression alone that characterises much informal, self-directed return-to-running guidance.\n\n**Criteria-Based Rather Than Time-Based Progression**\n\nCriteria-based progression uses functional tests and symptom response rather than calendar time alone: single-leg hop test performance (within 90% of the uninjured side), single-leg squat quality, and pain response to the previous training session (no significant symptom increase) all inform readiness to progress — this individualises the return timeline appropriately rather than imposing an arbitrary fixed schedule regardless of the individual's actual recovery trajectory.\n\n**The 10% Rule as a Starting Reference Point**\n\nThe traditional 10% rule provides a conservative starting reference point for volume progression once continuous running is re-established, though genuinely individualised progression based on symptom response, applying the criteria-based principles above, is preferable to rigid adherence to this rule regardless of individual response.\n\n**Cross-Training During Early Return Phases**\n\nCross-training (swimming, cycling, aqua jogging) maintains cardiovascular fitness during early return phases when running volume must remain low, supporting both physical conditioning and psychological wellbeing during the return process — genuinely reducing the temptation to progress running volume too rapidly purely to address fitness loss concerns that cross-training can otherwise address.\n\n**Applying Return-to-Running Principles Across Conditions**\n\nThe structured, criteria-based return-to-running framework established in this slide applies across the range of specific running injuries covered throughout this course — Achilles tendinopathy, MTSS, stress fractures, ITBS, and plantar fasciopathy — representing a consistent, evidence-based approach to safely transitioning from injury management back to full training, rather than a condition-specific protocol applicable only to one presentation.",
