        id: "s11", heading: "Bone Stress Injury: The Continuum Model",
        body: "Bone stress injury exists on a continuum, and understanding this continuum model directly informs both diagnostic approach and graduated return-to-loading protocols across the stress fracture presentations covered earlier in this course.\n\n**The Continuum: Stress Reaction to Displaced Fracture**\n\nBone stress injury progresses from stress reaction (early bone marrow oedema without cortical disruption, visible only on MRI) through stress fracture (partial or complete cortical disruption) to displaced fracture — this continuum framing, rather than a binary \"fractured or not\" classification, better reflects the genuine spectrum of bone stress injury severity encountered clinically.\n\n**Low-Risk Versus High-Risk Sites**\n\nLow-risk stress fractures (most metatarsal shafts, posteromedial tibia, fibula) generally heal well with relative rest and progressive reloading over 6-8 weeks. High-risk stress fractures (anterior tibial cortex, navicular as established in the earlier dedicated slide, fifth metatarsal, femoral neck) carry substantially higher delayed union, non-union, or complete fracture risk, often requiring longer non-weight-bearing periods and sometimes surgical fixation.\n\n**The Fredericson MRI Grading System**\n\nThe Fredericson MRI grading system (Grade 1-4, based on periosteal and bone marrow oedema extent) helps predict healing time and informs the necessary period of load modification — higher grades require longer periods before progressive return to impact loading, providing objective grading to supplement clinical assessment.\n\n**Risk Factor Assessment Beyond Mechanical Loading**\n\nRisk factor assessment for any bone stress injury should always include nutritional status (relative energy deficiency in sport, RED-S, covered in detail in the dedicated earlier slide), menstrual history in female athletes (functional hypothalamic amenorrhoea is strongly associated with bone stress injury, as established in the Female Runners slide), and vitamin D status — recognising that bone stress injury frequently reflects a combination of mechanical loading and underlying bone health factors, rather than mechanical overload alone.\n\n**Integrating Continuum Thinking with Site-Specific Management**\n\nApplying this continuum model alongside the site-specific risk stratification (low versus high-risk locations) and the broader risk factor assessment described above provides the comprehensive clinical framework needed for accurate diagnosis, appropriate imaging selection, and safe, evidence-based management of bone stress injury across the range of presentations covered throughout this course.",
