        body: "Relative Energy Deficiency in Sport (RED-S) describes the physiological consequences of inadequate energy availability relative to training energy expenditure, and recognising RED-S is directly relevant to the bone stress injury content covered earlier in this course.\n\n**Beyond the Female Athlete Triad**\n\nRED-S extends beyond the previously narrower \"Female Athlete Triad\" concept to recognise impacts across multiple body systems in both male and female athletes — an important conceptual broadening, since energy deficiency consequences are not limited to female athletes alone despite the condition's historical framing.\n\n**Consequences Across Multiple Body Systems**\n\nConsequences include impaired bone health (substantially elevated stress fracture risk, directly relevant to the bone stress injury continuum established earlier in this course), menstrual dysfunction in female athletes, impaired immune function, cardiovascular effects, and impaired training adaptation and performance — making RED-S relevant to virtually any athlete presenting with recurrent or unusual injury patterns, not solely those with obvious disordered eating presentations.\n\n**Screening Questions for Any Athlete with Stress Fracture**\n\nScreening questions for any athlete presenting with stress fracture should include training volume and recent changes, dietary patterns and any history of disordered eating, menstrual history in female athletes (amenorrhoea or oligomenorrhoea, as established in the bone stress injury slide), and fatigue or recurrent illness patterns — these questions should be incorporated routinely into stress fracture assessment, not reserved only for cases with obvious clinical suspicion.\n\n**Appropriate Referral Pathway**\n\nRecognition of RED-S risk factors should prompt referral to sports medicine physician and dietitian rather than focusing solely on local biomechanical management of the presenting stress fracture, since addressing the underlying energy deficiency is essential to preventing recurrence — local treatment alone, without addressing this systemic contributing factor, risks ongoing or recurrent bone stress injury.\n\n**RED-S as a Recurring Consideration Throughout This Course**\n\nThis RED-S framework directly informs the risk factor assessment established in the bone stress injury continuum slide and the menstrual history considerations covered in the Female Runners slide, representing an important, recurring systemic consideration underlying the mechanically-focused injury content covered throughout much of this course.",
