        id: "s13", heading: "Compartment Syndrome: Acute vs Chronic Exertional",
        body: "Acute and chronic exertional compartment syndrome represent fundamentally different clinical entities despite sharing anatomical terminology, and accurate distinction between them is essential given their dramatically different urgency and management implications.\n\n**Acute Compartment Syndrome: A True Surgical Emergency**\n\nAcute compartment syndrome is a surgical emergency, typically following significant trauma, characterised by severe pain disproportionate to injury, pain on passive muscle stretch, paraesthesia, and eventually pulselessness — a late and genuinely ominous sign. Any suspicion requires immediate orthopaedic referral for compartment pressure measurement and emergency fasciotomy if confirmed; delay risks permanent muscle and nerve damage.\n\n**Chronic Exertional Compartment Syndrome: A Distinct, Non-Emergency Condition**\n\nChronic exertional compartment syndrome (CECS) is an entirely distinct, non-emergency condition presenting with exercise-induced lower leg pain and tightness that builds predictably during exercise and resolves with rest, typically within 20-30 minutes — this predictable, exercise-and-rest-dependent pattern fundamentally distinguishes CECS from the acute, traumatic, rapidly progressive presentation of acute compartment syndrome.\n\n**Compartment Distribution**\n\nThe anterior compartment is most commonly affected in runners with CECS, though deep posterior compartment involvement can mimic MTSS, established earlier in this course — adding a further differential consideration when assessing exercise-related lower leg pain in runners.\n\n**Diagnosis Requires Compartment Pressure Testing**\n\nDiagnosis requires compartment pressure testing before and after standardised exercise, with elevated post-exercise pressures confirming the diagnosis — this objective testing requirement distinguishes CECS diagnosis from the largely clinical diagnosis applicable to most other running-related conditions covered throughout this course.\n\n**Management Options**\n\nConservative management (gait retraining toward reduced impact loading, activity modification) has limited evidence of success for CECS specifically; fasciotomy remains the definitive treatment for cases significantly limiting athletic participation, with good outcomes reported in properly selected patients — reflecting that CECS, unlike many of the other running-related conditions covered in this course, often requires surgical rather than purely conservative management for meaningful symptom resolution.",
