        id: "s17", heading: "Masters Runners: Age-Related Considerations",
        body: "Masters runners (typically defined as over 35-40 years) present distinct considerations related to age-related physiological changes affecting both injury risk and recovery capacity, requiring modified clinical assessment compared with younger athletes covered elsewhere in this course.\n\n**Age-Related Tendon and Connective Tissue Changes**\n\nTendon and connective tissue changes with age include reduced collagen turnover and increased stiffness, contributing to higher rates of degenerative tendinopathy — directly relevant to the tendon continuum model established in the Biomechanics and Orthotics course, since masters runners are more likely to present with degenerative-stage rather than purely reactive-stage tendinopathy.\n\n**Elevated Achilles Rupture Risk in Asymptomatic Tendons**\n\nAs established in the Biomechanics and Orthotics course, 30-35% of asymptomatic adults over 50 already have degenerative Achilles changes on imaging — relevant when masters runners present with sudden-onset symptoms after sudden increased loading, since these tendons carry elevated rupture risk given their pre-existing, often asymptomatic degenerative changes.\n\n**Modified Recovery and Training Periodisation**\n\nRecovery time between training sessions increases with age, requiring modified training periodisation with greater emphasis on recovery days and potentially reduced peak training frequency compared with younger counterparts, while total weekly volume can often be maintained through different distribution across the training week.\n\n**Bone Density Considerations**\n\nBone density changes, particularly post-menopausal in women, elevate stress fracture risk, reinforcing the importance of strength training (established in the dedicated earlier slide) and adequate calcium and vitamin D status as part of comprehensive masters runner management.\n\n**Age Should Not Discourage Running Participation**\n\nImportantly, age alone should not be used to discourage running participation — running maintains cardiovascular health, bone density, and functional capacity, with appropriately individualised training load established throughout this course's load management content. Masters runner management requires thoughtful adaptation of the principles covered throughout this curriculum, not blanket activity restriction based on age alone.",
