      { q: "A defining difference between running and walking gait is that running has:", opts: ["Two periods of double support per cycle","A float (flight) phase with no foot in contact with the ground","A longer stance phase than walking","No swing phase"], a: 1, exp: "Running replaces walking\u2019s double-support periods with a float phase in which neither foot contacts the ground, and stance shortens substantially \u2014 concentrating load over a briefer contact time and raising tissue stress." },
      { q: "Medial tibial stress syndrome (MTSS) is best distinguished from a tibial stress fracture by:", opts: ["Sharply focal pain over a small point on the bone","Diffuse pain along the posteromedial tibial border that often eases as the athlete warms up","Pain that is worst at complete rest","A positive Thompson test"], a: 1, exp: "MTSS produces diffuse pain spread over several centimetres of the posteromedial tibia that frequently eases with warm-up, whereas a stress fracture causes focal, point-tender pain that worsens with continued loading and warrants imaging." },
      { q: "RED-S (Relative Energy Deficiency in Sport) is best described as:", opts: ["An overuse injury of the Achilles tendon", "Low energy availability impairing multiple body systems, including bone and endocrine health", "A grading system for tibial stress fractures", "Excess caloric intake reducing performance"], a: 1, exp: "The IOC consensus (Mountjoy et al., 2018) defines RED-S as impaired function across multiple body systems caused by low energy availability, extending the original female athlete triad to affect bone, endocrine, metabolic and cardiovascular health in athletes of both sexes." },
      { q: "A key age-related consideration when advising masters (older) runners is:", opts: ["Greater tendon elasticity than younger runners","Reduced tendon compliance and slower tissue recovery, so adaptation needs longer","Higher bone density than younger runners","Faster healing of stress injuries"], a: 1, exp: "With age, tendons stiffen and tissue recovery slows, so masters runners benefit from longer adaptation periods, greater recovery between hard sessions, and attention to strength to offset age-related muscle loss." },
      { q: "Iliotibial band compression against the lateral femoral epicondyle occurs at approximately what knee flexion angle?", opts: ["10 degrees", "30 degrees", "60 degrees", "90 degrees"], a: 1, exp: "The IT band compresses at approximately 30 degrees of knee flexion — the impingement angle during the loading response phase of gait, when ground reaction forces are highest, explaining why downhill running exacerbates ITBS." },
      { q: "A widely used criterion for safely returning to running after injury is:", opts: ["Complete, permanent absence of any muscle soreness","Pain-free walking with the ability to progress load gradually without a symptom flare","Returning only after a fixed 6 months regardless of symptoms","Immediately resuming previous weekly mileage"], a: 1, exp: "Return to running is guided by symptom response rather than time alone: the athlete should be pain-free in walking and able to increase load gradually (for example a graded walk-run progression) without provoking a symptom flare." },
      { q: "Acute compartment syndrome is distinguished from chronic exertional compartment syndrome by:", opts: ["Bilateral versus unilateral presentation", "Being a surgical emergency with severe disproportionate pain, versus predictable exercise-induced pain resolving with rest", "Affecting only the anterior compartment", "Occurring only in untrained individuals"], a: 1, exp: "Acute compartment syndrome is a surgical emergency with severe pain disproportionate to injury requiring immediate referral. Chronic exertional compartment syndrome presents with predictable exercise-induced pain resolving within 20-30 minutes of rest — a fundamentally different, non-emergency condition." },
      { q: "Strength training for injury prevention in runners has what evidence base?", opts: ["No supporting evidence", "Weak observational evidence only", "Strong RCT and systematic review evidence for injury risk reduction", "Evidence only in elite athletes"], a: 2, exp: "Lauersen et al. (2014, BJSM) meta-analysis demonstrates strong evidence for strength training reducing injury risk in runners, alongside improving running economy — providing both performance and injury-prevention benefit." },
      { q: "The comfort filter hypothesis in running shoe selection proposes that:", opts: ["Motion-control shoes should be prescribed by foot type", "Runners naturally select footwear suited to their biomechanics based on subjective comfort", "All runners should transition to minimalist footwear", "Shoe cushioning has no effect on injury risk"], a: 1, exp: "The comfort filter hypothesis, with reasonable supporting evidence, proposes that runners naturally select footwear suited to their individual biomechanics when choosing based on comfort — contradicting the traditional motion-control prescription model based on static foot type assessment." },
      { q: "The Lauersen et al. (2014) meta-analysis found the single most effective category of intervention for preventing sports injuries was:", opts: ["Static stretching before activity", "Strength training", "Proprioceptive balance drills alone", "Longer general warm-ups"], a: 1, exp: "Strength training was markedly more effective than stretching or proprioception alone, roughly halving overuse injuries — making it the strongest evidence-based pillar of injury-prevention programming." }
